@TheCardanoTimes A few project have it figured out. Most are nerds building things for other nerds - not mass adoption. 

I'm just a normal user. I LOVE Cardano - because it's trustworthy. I've been a user since 2021 & will never leave. I don't trust SOL. I don't trust ETH. I trust BTC & Cardano. That's it. 

Here are a few examples of platforms I use regularly (or semi-regularly) based on a decent UI that I can understand as an everyday guy:

@strikeperps - My favorite. Easily beats staking ROI (by a lot). Simple & effective. Doesn't try to solve all the world's problems.

@MinswapDEX  - my go-to DEX. Trustworthy, super intuitive, the leadership team rewards users, and it's been very reliable. They are future looking, and communicate well.

@liqwidfinance - less intuitive than the two above, but still very useable. Used to use this quite a bit, but found better ROI elsewhere.

@Indigo_protocol - It took me forever to understand synthetics (this is nerdery - I don't recommend new projects start here), but now that I do, I dabble. I don't think most regular users would care to spend the time it takes to learn.

@IagonOfficial - I have a little bit in Iagon, but mostly because I was curious. I still don't understand all of how it works, but I understand the "why". I have no idea if this will catch on, but it's interesting & makes sense. 

Lots of the other projects I've looked at are ok, but having hired tons of engineers in the past... I can tell immediately who builds things WITHOUT customer engagement in the design process, and who gets customer input/requirements before launching. 

Of all the software engineers I've hired over the years, only 10% or so could ever get out of the "well, it works in the lab - the customer must be stupid" mindset. That 10% ended up as management. The rest languished, because they did not understand business. 

This is a dev maturity issue. No business should ever - ever - ever build a product in a vacuum without speaking to the customer base first.

