@yutazzz @Karl_Fren For the record, during the initial node diversity workshop we had a presentation from a gentleman who does a lot of work in the Ethereum ecosystem on node conformance testing, and the target there for "safe" diversity is preferably no single node architecture making more than 33% of blocks. So if one is bad, two is better, but three or more (within reason, we don't need a node in every language) is the ideal point (I think we currently have 6-7 different language versions currently in development).

Another, more poignant question for me, given the current size of the Cardano developer ecosystem, is how much cross over between teams is there working on "alternative nodes" because the same engineers working in two or three teams generally defeats the purpose of having more eyes looking for bugs and errors.

Anyway, I'm not for or against any of the current proposals. These are good questions that should be asked of everyone. How many Haskell devs have come to the Cardano ecosystem? How many are there? Etc...

